properties.Title: Alberta Emergency Alert - Telephone Service Alert
properties.Summary:
Description: Due to a wide spread wireless degradation, service for TELUS customers has been disrupted. This means that anyone in this area affected may be unable to contact Police, Fire and Ambulance by telephone if they have an emergency. The persons affected by this disruption should call 587-370-4681 should they require emergency services in the Taber or MD of Taber area. ### Telus has advised that there is a wide spread wireless degradation issue happening this morning. Telus teams are investigating. Telus clients may not be able to complete or connect to the network therefore not able to call 9 1 1.
Expires: 2020-04-07T10:26:09-06:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Town of Taber, 2020-03-31T10:24:19-06:00, NAADS-CA-AB-AEA1-6286
Area: MD of Taber
properties.Author: Town of Taber

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A weather system is spreading snow through the northern grainbelt this morning. Snow began in Meadow Lake overnight and will gradually diminish this afternoon. Total snowfall amounts for Meadow Lake are forecast to be in the 10 - 15 cm range. Snow will begin in Prince Albert this morning and continue throughout the day before tapering off later this afternoon. Snowfall amounts are forecast to be 10 cm in Prince Albert. Snow will be heavy at times resulting in reduced visibility. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.
Expires: 2020-04-01T02:22:21-00:00

properties.Summary:

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A strong low pressure system is forecast to track northward out of the Dakotas on Thursday. The track of this low is uncertain at this time, however it does have the potential to spread heavy snow over portions of southern and central Manitoba. Current indications are that snow will spread into southern Manitoba Thursday morning, working its way north throughout the day. It should end Thursday night in the south and on Friday in central Manitoba. A mixture of rain and snow could also occur in more eastern locales, again depending on the track of the system and how long the mild airmass remains in place. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.
Expires: 2020-04-01T13:50:01-00:00

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 20 cm is expected. A strengthening low pressure system will track northward out of the Dakotas on Wednesday, giving heavy wet snow to areas near the Saskatchewan Manitoba border. The snow will begin early in the morning in the south and work its way northward throughout the day. Current indications are that 10 to 20 cm will fall with this system, although local amounts could be higher. Some surrounding regions may also be added as the system moves in, depending on the track of the system. As you go east, amounts will be less as the precipitation will be lighter and transition to rain. Localized areas of freezing rain are also possible, however the main impact of this system will be snow. ### Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

Description: Poor visibility in snow and blowing snow is expected or occurring in some locations. Total snowfall: 10 to 20 cm. Locations: Nain and vicinity. Time span: Wednesday morning to Thursday evening. Remarks: Light snow will begin tonight and intensify on Wednesday afternoon, persisting until Thursday evening. Moderate northeasterly winds will increase tonight and combine with fresh fallen snow to reduce visibility in blowing snow, especially Wednesday night and Thursday. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blowing snow advisories are issued when winds are expected to create blowing snow giving poor visibility to 800 metres or less for at least 3 hours. properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow beginning this afternoon changing to rain Wednesday. Snowfall total: 5 to 10 cm. Rainfall total: 20 to 40 mm. Location: northeastern New Brunswick. Remarks: Periods of snow tonight will change to rain on Wednesday as temperatures rise above zero. An extended period of rain is then expected to last until Thursday night, when temperatures should fall below zero again. At this time, precipitation should change to flurries and taper off by Friday morning. Temperatures will remain above freezing through the overnight hours on Wednesday. The rain and mild temperatures could lead to significant melting of the snow pack and runoff. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.
